    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-23T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-23T05:00:00-05:00" n="220"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d220">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/503: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-23T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 23, 1939—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received September 23—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>595. The communiqué of the General Staff for September 22, published this morning
                    states that on September 22, the units of the Red <pb facs="0221" n="209"
                        xml:id="pg_209"/> army occupied the town of Belostok<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d220fn11">Bialystok.</note> and the fortress of Brest Litovsk<note
                        n="12" xml:id="d220fn12">Brześć and Bugiem.</note> and continued mopping up
                    the remnants of the Polish Army in the forest of Antust to the northwest of the
                    town of Grodno.<note n="13" xml:id="d220fn13">Gardinas.</note> The communiqué
                    continues that units of the Red army have cleared out the remnants of the Polish
                    Army and “officer groups” in the region of Sarny and that in the region of
                        Lwow<note n="14" xml:id="d220fn14">Lvov, Lemberg.</note> 6 Polish infantry
                    divisions and 2 regiments of sharpshooters, headed by General Langer, had
                    surrendered. The communiqué concludes that in the period from September 17 to
                    September 21, 120,000 officers and men have been taken prisoner with the capture
                    of 380 cannon and 1,400 machine guns.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[For the note of protest made on September 30, 1939, by the Polish Government
                        against the Boundary and Friendship Treaty between Germany and the Soviet
                        Union signed at Moscow on September 28, 1939, see <ref
                            target="frus1939v01#pg_462">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1939, volume I, page
                        462</ref>. The text of the treaty is in <hi rend="italic">Nazi-Soviet
                            Relations, 1939–1941</hi>, page 105; or, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Reichsgesetzblatt</hi>, 1940, Teil II, No. 1 (January 5, 1940), page 4,
                        including the additional protocol of October 4, 1939; or, <hi rend="italic"
                            >Documents on German Foreign Policy, 1918–1945</hi>, Series D, volume
                        VIII, page 167.]</p>
                </postscript>
                <postscript>
                    <p>[A statement by the Secretary of State was issued on October 2, 1939, wherein
                        it was declared that, although Poland had become the victim of force, the
                        United States continued to regard the Government of Poland as in existence.
                        For text, see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, October
                        7, 1939, page 342.]</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
